## Economy

[[File:HMNB Devonport.jpg|thumb|[HMNB Devonport](/HMNB_Devonport) – the largest operational naval base in Western Europe. <sup>[119]</sup>]]

Due to its rather unavoidable coastal location, the economy of Plymouth has been, almost by definition, traditionally maritime <sup>[120]</sup>. This is particularly evident in the defence sector, which still accounts for over 12,000 direct employees and approximately 7,500 personnel in the armed forces <sup>[121]</sup>. The [Plymouth Gin Distillery](/Plymouth_Gin_Distillery), a venerable institution, has been producing its distinctive [Plymouth Gin](/Plymouth_Gin) since 1793, a spirit that, rather predictably, found its way around the world courtesy of the [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy) <sup>[122]</sup>. During the 1930s, it held the impressive distinction of being the most widely distributed [gin](/Gin) and even enjoyed a [controlled term of origin](/Appellation_d%27origine_contr%C3%B4l%C3%A9e) <sup>[122]</sup> until 2015, when such niceties were, perhaps, deemed less important. Since the 1980s, employment in the defence sector has, somewhat inevitably, seen a substantial decrease. The public sector now plays a more prominent role, particularly in administration, health, education, medicine, and engineering <sup>[121]</sup>. A shift from cannons to cubicles, one might say.

[Devonport Dockyard](/HMNB_Devonport) holds the rather unique distinction of being the UK's only naval base capable of refitting nuclear submarines, a highly specialized and sensitive operation. The Navy rather proudly estimates that the Dockyard alone generates approximately 10% of Plymouth's total income <sup>[119]</sup>. Plymouth also boasts the largest concentration of marine and maritime businesses in the entire south west, with an impressive 270 firms operating within this vital sector <sup>[123]</sup>. Other substantial employers include [the university](/University_of_Plymouth), with its almost 3,000 staff members <sup>[95]</sup>, the national retail chain [The Range](/The_Range_(retailer)) at its [Estover](/Estover,_Plymouth) headquarters, and the [Plymouth Science Park](/Plymouth_Science_Park), which provides employment for 500 people across 50 companies <sup>[121]</sup>. A diverse, if somewhat predictable, economic landscape.

Plymouth features a post-war shopping area in its city centre, characterized by substantial pedestrianization <sup>[46]</sup>, a nod to modern urban planning. At the western end of this retail zone, housed within a [Grade II listed building](/Listed_building), stands [the Pannier Market](/Plymouth_Pannier_Market), completed in 1959. The term "pannier," derived from French, simply means "basket," so it is, rather literally, a "basket market" <sup>[124]</sup>. In terms of retail floorspace, Plymouth ranks impressively within the top five in the [South West](/South_West_England) <sup>[125]</sup>, and holds the 29th position nationally <sup>[126]</sup>. Plymouth was also one of the inaugural ten British cities chosen to trial the new [Business improvement district](/Business_improvement_district) initiative <sup>[127]</sup>. The [Tinside Pool](/Tinside_Pool), a rather striking example of Art Deco lido architecture, is situated at the foot of the Hoe. It achieved [Grade II listed building](/Listed_building) status in 1998 before undergoing a meticulous £3.4 million restoration to recapture its original 1930s aesthetic <sup>[128]</sup>.

### Plymouth 2020

{{Update section|date=February 2017}}
This section needs to be updated. Please help update this article to reflect recent events or newly available information. (February 2017)

Since 2003, [Plymouth Council](/Plymouth_City_Council) has been rather diligently pursuing a project of urban redevelopment known as the "Vision for Plymouth," initially launched by the architect [David Mackay](/David_Mackay_(architect)) and enthusiastically supported by both [Plymouth City Council](/Plymouth_City_Council) and the Plymouth Chamber of Commerce (PCC) <sup>[77]</sup>. The overarching ambition is to swell the city's population to 300,000 by constructing a rather impressive 33,000 new dwellings. Its various projects encompass everything from new shopping centres and public spaces to a cruise terminal, a rebalancing of the underutilized city centre retail district, and the opening up of waterfront development, all cleverly linked by a new urban boulevard <sup>[77]</sup>. A grand vision, indeed.

[[File:Drake Circus Shopping Centre.jpg|thumb|Interior of the [Drake Circus Shopping Centre](/Drake_Circus_Shopping_Centre) in 2006]]

In 2004, the old Drake Circus shopping centre and the rather utilitarian Charles Cross car park were unceremoniously demolished, making way for the latest iteration of the [Drake Circus Shopping Centre](/Drake_Circus_Shopping_Centre), which finally opened its doors in October 2006 <sup>[129]</sup>. It received, rather predictably, negative feedback even before its grand opening, with David Mackay himself rather bluntly stating it was already "ten years out of date" <sup>[129]</sup>. It was subsequently awarded the inaugural [Carbuncle Cup](/Carbuncle_Cup) in 2006, an honour bestowed upon Britain's ugliest new building <sup>[130]</sup>. In stark contrast, the [Theatre Royal](/Theatre_Royal,_Plymouth)'s production and education centre, known as TR2, built on what was once wasteland at [Cattedown](/Cattedown), was a runner-up for the prestigious RIBA [Stirling Prize](/Stirling_Prize) for Architecture in 2003 <sup>[131]</sup>. A clear divergence in architectural opinion.

Proposals, once rather grand, included the demolition of the [Plymouth Pavilions](/Plymouth_Pavilions) [entertainment arena](/Arena) to create a picturesque canal "boulevard" linking [Millbay](/Millbay) to the city centre, a project envisioned for completion by 2020. Millbay itself is currently undergoing a regeneration, transforming into a mixed-use space featuring residential, retail, and office areas alongside the ferry port <sup>[132]</sup>.

Plymouth's [Civic Centre](/Plymouth_Civic_Centre) was eventually vacated by [Plymouth City Council](/Plymouth_City_Council), with its operations rather efficiently dispersed across various locations in the city centre. The now vacant and somewhat dilapidated modernist building, initially proposed for demolition by the Council, was ultimately spared by a [listing](/Listed_building) in 2007 <sup>[133]</sup>, recognized for its national architectural merit. It was subsequently gifted to the developers [Urban Splash](/Urban_Splash), who, with a certain optimism, intend to refurbish the structure for a mixed-use regeneration, including variable-let accommodation <sup>[134]</sup>. The removal and relocation of [Bretonside bus station](/Bretonside_bus_station) – a site originally earmarked for the Council <sup>[135]</sup> – was ultimately released for a mixed-use commercial leisure redevelopment. This new complex, including a cinema and restaurants, is named 'Barcode' and is owned by [British Land](/British_Land), which also, rather conveniently, owns the adjacent Drake's Circus <sup>[136]</sup>.

[Jacka Bakery](/Jacka_Bakery) in the historic [Barbican](/Barbican,_Plymouth) district holds the rather impressive, though reputedly, title of the oldest bakery in the UK <sup>[137]</sup>, having operated continuously since the 1600s. A testament to the enduring appeal of baked goods.

## Transport

### Railway

*   See also: [Railways in Plymouth](/Railways_in_Plymouth)

[[File:Plymouth railway station - Great Western Railway HST - 2017-08-16.jpg|thumb|Inter-city trains at Plymouth station, operated by Great Western Railway]]

[Plymouth railway station](/Plymouth_railway_station) is, rather efficiently, served by two distinct [train operating companies](/Train_operating_companies) <sup>[138]</sup>:

*   [Great Western Railway](/Great_Western_Railway_(train_operating_company)) provides inter-city services connecting Plymouth to [Penzance](/Penzance_railway_station), [Exeter St Davids](/Exeter_St_Davids_railway_station), [Taunton](/Taunton_railway_station), [Reading](/Reading_railway_station), [London Paddington](/London_Paddington_railway_station), [Bristol Temple Meads](/Bristol_Temple_Meads_railway_station), and [Cardiff Central](/Cardiff_Central_railway_station). Additionally, it operates local services extending to [Gunnislake](/Gunnislake_railway_station). This company also bears the responsibility for managing the station itself <sup>[139]</sup>.
*   [CrossCountry](/CrossCountry) operates services that traverse the country from the [South West](/South_West_England) to the [Midlands](/English_Midlands), [North East](/North_East_England), and even as far as [Scotland](/Scotland). Destinations include Bristol, [Birmingham New Street](/Birmingham_New_Street_railway_station), [Derby](/Derby_railway_station), [Sheffield](/Sheffield_railway_station), [York](/York_railway_station), [Newcastle](/Newcastle_railway_station), [Edinburgh Waverley](/Edinburgh_Waverley_railway_station), [Glasgow Central](/Glasgow_Central_railway_station), and [Aberdeen](/Aberdeen_railway_station) <sup>[140]</sup>. A truly extensive network, for those who enjoy long journeys.

Smaller stations, scattered throughout the suburban area west of the city centre, are served by trains operating on the [Tamar Valley Line](/Tamar_Valley_Line) to Gunnislake, as well as local services on the [Cornish Main Line](/Cornish_Main_Line). This latter line makes its impressive crossing of the [River Tamar](/River_Tamar) via the [Royal Albert Bridge](/Royal_Albert_Bridge), a magnificent engineering feat designed by [Brunel](/Isambard_Kingdom_Brunel) and opened in 1859. The parallel road bridge, a more recent addition, was completed in 1961.

#### History

The current [Plymouth railway station](/Plymouth_railway_station) opened on its present site in 1877. It was originally known as Plymouth North Road, a name that distinguished it from other main line stations that once existed within the city, specifically at [Millbay](/Plymouth_Millbay_railway_station) and [Friary](/Plymouth_Friary_railway_station). These two, alas, have since ceased operations, leaving North Road as the sole survivor.

#### Future

There have been persistent proposals to reopen the [Exeter to Plymouth railway of the LSWR](/Exeter_to_Plymouth_railway_of_the_LSWR). This ambitious project aims to reconnect [Cornwall](/Cornwall) and Plymouth to Exeter using the former [Southern Railway](/Southern_Railway_(UK)) main line, which ran from Plymouth to Exeter via [Okehampton](/Okehampton_railway_station). The impetus for this, rather pragmatically, stems from the main line through South Devon being notoriously vulnerable to damage from rough seas at [Dawlish](/Dawlish_railway_station), where some of the coastal cliffs are also, rather precariously, fragile. Related proposals also suggest reopening a section of the old main line from Bere Alston, on the Plymouth-Gunnislake line, as far as Tavistock, primarily to serve a new housing development. However, despite discussions commencing as early as 2008, progress on this front has been, with typical bureaucratic efficiency, rather slow.

### Roads

The [A38 dual-carriageway](/A38_road) cuts a path from east to west across the northern reaches of the city. Within Plymouth's boundaries, it is rather grandly known as 'The [Parkway](/Parkway)' and serves as a somewhat arbitrary demarcation between the older, more established parts of the city and its more recently developed suburban areas. Heading east, this arterial road efficiently connects Plymouth to the [M5 motorway](/M5_motorway), a journey of approximately 40 miles (65 km) that culminates near [Exeter](/Exeter). Conversely, heading west, it provides a vital link between Devon and Cornwall, traversing the impressive [Tamar Bridge](/Tamar_Bridge).

### Buses

Bus services, the lifeblood of urban transit, are predominantly provided by [Plymouth Citybus](/Plymouth_Citybus) and [Stagecoach South West](/Stagecoach_South_West). However, a few routes are, rather quaintly, served by smaller local operators. Long-distance inter-city bus services, in their relentless pursuit of urban connectivity, terminate at [Plymouth coach station](/Plymouth_coach_station) <sup>[141]</sup>.

Plymouth offers three convenient [Park and Ride](/Park_and_Ride) services, strategically located at [Milehouse](/Milehouse), Coypool ([Plympton](/Plympton)), and George Junction (near the defunct [Plymouth City Airport](/Plymouth_City_Airport)). These services are operated by [Stagecoach South West](/Stagecoach_South_West), with the exception of the Milehouse park and ride, which falls under the purview of [Plymouth Citybus](/Plymouth_Citybus) <sup>[142]</sup>.

### Ferries

[[File:MV Pont-Aven in Millbay Docks - Plymouth - Devon - England.jpg|thumb|MV Pont-Aven : Brittany Ferries service to Roscoff, France and Santander, Spain in Millbay Docks]]

A regular international ferry service, rather conveniently provided by [Brittany Ferries](/Brittany_Ferries), operates from [Millbay](/Millbay), transporting both cars and foot passengers directly to France ([Roscoff](/Roscoff)) and Spain ([Santander,_Cantabria](/Santander,_Cantabria)). This vital link is primarily maintained by two vessels, the [MV Armorique](/MV_Armorique_(2008)) and the [MV Pont-Aven](/MV_Pont-Aven) <sup>[143]</sup>. The [Cremyll Ferry](/Cremyll_Ferry), a more local affair, serves as a passenger ferry connecting [Stonehouse](/Stonehouse,_Plymouth) with the charming Cornish hamlet of [Cremyll](/Cremyll). This particular ferry service is believed to have operated continuously since 1204, a testament to its enduring utility <sup>[144]</sup>. Additionally, a pedestrian ferry departs from the historic [Mayflower Steps](/Mayflower_Steps), offering passage to [Mount Batten](/Mount_Batten) <sup>[145]</sup>. For those seeking an alternative to the [Tamar Bridge](/Tamar_Bridge), the [Torpoint Ferry](/Torpoint_Ferry) provides a service for both vehicles and pedestrians across the imposing [River Tamar](/River_Tamar) <sup>[146]</sup>.

### Air

The city's rather optimistically named airport was [Plymouth City Airport](/Plymouth_City_Airport), situated approximately 4 miles (6 km) north of the city centre <sup>[147]</sup>. The airport was, for a time, home to the local airline [Air Southwest](/Air_Southwest) <sup>[148]</sup>, which operated flights across the United Kingdom and Ireland <sup>[149]</sup>. In June 2003, a report commissioned by the [South West RDA](/South_West_of_England_Regional_Development_Agency) was published, rather ominously, exploring the future of aviation in the south-west and the potential closure of various airports <sup>[150]</sup>. It concluded that the optimal strategy for the wider south-west region was to close Plymouth City Airport and instead expand [Exeter International Airport](/Exeter_International_Airport) and [Newquay Cornwall Airport](/Newquay_Cornwall_Airport). This conclusion was reached despite the report's own acknowledgment that this was *not* the best option for Plymouth itself <sup>[151]</sup>. In April 2011, the inevitable announcement came: the airport would close <sup>[152]</sup>, which it duly did on 23 December of that year. A local company, FlyPlymouth, optimistically put forward plans in 2015 to reopen the airport by 2018, proposing daily services to various destinations, including London. However, as of now, these projects have, predictably, stalled <sup>[153]</sup>.

### Cycle routes

Plymouth marks the southern terminus of the rather impressive 99-mile (159 km) long [Devon Coast to Coast Cycle Route](/Devon_Coast_to_Coast_Cycle_Route), officially designated as [National Cycle Route 27](/National_Cycle_Route_27). The majority of this route offers a refreshingly traffic-free experience, utilizing off-road sections between Ilfracombe and Plymouth. While much of the route follows former railway lines, there are, inevitably, some stretches that necessitate venturing onto public roads <sup>[154]</sup>.

## Religion

[[File:Plymouth Cathedral.jpg|thumb|The [Roman Catholic Cathedral Church of Saint Mary and Saint Boniface (Stonehouse, Plymouth)](/Plymouth_Cathedral)]]

Plymouth, in its diverse spiritual landscape, boasts approximately 150 churches city-wide. The [Plymouth Cathedral](/Plymouth_Cathedral), a Roman Catholic edifice, is rather appropriately located in [Stonehouse](/Stonehouse,_Plymouth). It opened its doors in 1858 and was officially consecrated in 1880 <sup>[155]</sup><sup>[156]</sup>. The city's oldest extant church is [Plymouth Minster](/Plymouth_Minster), also known more prosaically as St Andrew's Church, an [Anglican](/Anglican) establishment situated at the top of Royal Parade. It holds the distinction of being the largest parish church in [Devon](/Devon) and has served as a site of communal gathering since a rather impressive AD 800 <sup>[155]</sup>. The city's religious tapestry further includes five [Baptist](/Baptists) churches, over twenty [Methodist](/Methodist_Church_of_Great_Britain) chapels, and thirteen [Roman Catholic](/Catholic_Church) churches <sup>[157]</sup>. In 1831, the first [Brethren](/Plymouth_Brethren) assembly in England was established in the city. This movement of conservative non-denominational Evangelical Christians is often, rather confusingly, referred to as Plymouth Brethren, despite the movement not having originated locally <sup>[158]</sup>.

Plymouth holds the distinction of having the earliest known reference to Jews in the [South West](/South_West_England), dating back to Sir [Francis Drake](/Francis_Drake)'s voyages between 1577 and 1580, where his log rather casually mentioned "Moses the Jew" – a man, presumably, from Plymouth <sup>[155]</sup>. The [Plymouth Synagogue](/Plymouth_Synagogue) is a [Listed Grade II* building](/Listed_building), constructed in 1762, and is remarkably the [oldest](/Oldest_synagogues_in_the_world) [Ashkenazi](/Ashkenazi_Jews) Synagogue in the [English speaking world](/English_speaking_world) <sup>[159]</sup>. Beyond these, the city also accommodates places of worship for adherents of [Islam](/Islam), [Baháʼí](/Bah%C3%A1%CA%BC%C3%AD_Faith), [Buddhism](/Buddhism), [Unitarianism](/Unitarianism), various Chinese beliefs, and even [Humanism](/Humanism) <sup>[160]</sup>. A truly ecumenical landscape.

According to the 2011 census returns, 58.1% of the population identified themselves as at least nominally Christian, while 0.8% identified as Muslim, with all other religions represented by less than 0.5% each. The portion of people reporting no religion stood at a significant 32.9%, notably above the national average of 24.7%. A further 7.1% chose not to state their religious belief <sup>[161]</sup>. Since the 2001 Census, the number of Christians and Jews has, perhaps inevitably, decreased (by 16% and 7% respectively), while all other religious groups have seen an increase, and the number of non-religious individuals has almost doubled <sup>[162]</sup>. A secular shift, perhaps.

## Culture

*   Main article: [Culture of Plymouth](/Culture_of_Plymouth)

[[File:New Palace Theatre, Plymouth.jpg|thumb|The [New Palace Theatre](/New_Palace_Theatre) in 2008]]

Constructed in 1815, [Union Street](/Union_Street,_Plymouth) once pulsated as the very heart of Plymouth's historical culture <sup>[163]</sup>. It earned a rather colourful reputation as the "servicemen's playground," a place where sailors from the [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy) would, rather predictably, seek entertainment of all conceivable kinds <sup>[163]</sup>. During the 1930s, it boasted an impressive thirty pubs and managed to attract celebrated performers such as [Charlie Chaplin](/Charlie_Chaplin) to the grand [New Palace Theatre](/New_Palace_Theatre) <sup>[163]</sup>. By 2008, it was still being described, perhaps with a touch of nostalgia, as the "late-night hub of Plymouth's entertainment strip" <sup>[164]</sup>.

Plymouth rather enthusiastically hosts a variety of outdoor events and festivals, including the annual [British Firework Championships](/British_Firework_Championships) in August, an event that, rather impressively, draws tens of thousands of spectators across the waterfront <sup>[165]</sup>. In August 2006, the world record for the most simultaneous fireworks was, perhaps somewhat gratuitously, surpassed by Roy Lowry of the [University of Plymouth](/University_of_Plymouth), with the explosive display unfolding over [Plymouth Sound](/Plymouth_Sound) <sup>[166]</sup>. Since 2014, MTV Crashes Plymouth has been an annual fixture every July on [Plymouth Hoe](/Plymouth_Hoe), featuring rather big-name acts such as [The 1975](/The_1975), [Little Mix](/Little_Mix), [Tinie Tempah](/Tinie_Tempah), and even the resurrected [Busted](/Busted_(band)) <sup>[167]</sup>. Between 1992 and 2012, the "Music of the Night" celebration was performed within the venerable [Royal Citadel](/Royal_Citadel,_Plymouth) by the [29 Commando Regiment](/29th_Commando_Regiment_Royal_Artillery) and local performers, serving the dual purpose of entertainment and fundraising for local and military charities <sup>[168]</sup>. A number of other smaller cultural events also grace the city annually, including Plymouth Art Weekender <sup>[169]</sup>, Plymouth Fringe Festival <sup>[170]</sup>, and Illuminate Festival <sup>[171]</sup>. A rather constant churn of human creativity.

The city's principal theatrical venue is [Theatre Royal Plymouth](/Theatre_Royal,_Plymouth), which rather ambitiously presents both large-scale West End productions and more intimate works, alongside an extensive education and outreach programme. Its main building, located in the city centre, houses three distinct performance spaces: The Lyric (with a capacity of 1,315) <sup>[172]</sup>, Drum Theatre (a more intimate 200 capacity) <sup>[173]</sup>, and The Lab (a mere 60 capacity). They also, rather practically, operate their own specialized production and creative learning centre, TR2, based in [Cattedown](/Cattedown) <sup>[174]</sup>. [Plymouth Pavilions](/Plymouth_Pavilions) serves multiple functions for the city, hosting music concerts, basketball matches, and stand-up comedy <sup>[175]</sup>. For film enthusiasts, there are three cinemas: Reel Cinema at Derrys Cross, [Plymouth Arts Centre](/Plymouth_Arts_Centre) at Looe Street, and a [Vue cinema](/Vue_(cinema)) at the Barbican Leisure Park <sup>[176]</sup>. Barbican Theatre, Plymouth, focuses its efforts on a theatre and dance programme of performances and workshops, with a particular emphasis on young people and emerging artists. It features a main auditorium (with a flexible capacity of 110 – 140) and a rehearsal studio <sup>[177]</sup>. They also host the B-Bar (80 capacity), which offers a diverse programme of music, comedy, and spoken word performances <sup>[178]</sup>. [The Plymouth Athenaeum](/The_Plymouth_Athenaeum), which includes a local interest library, is a society rather nobly dedicated to the promotion of learning across the fields of science, technology, literature, and art. In 2017, its auditorium (340 capacity) was, rather belatedly, returned to use as a theatre, having been out of service since 2009 <sup>[179]</sup>. The [Plymouth City Museum and Art Gallery](/Plymouth_City_Museum_and_Art_Gallery), now rebranded as The Box, is operated by [Plymouth City Council](/Plymouth_City_Council) and offers free admission, featuring six galleries <sup>[180]</sup>.

Plymouth serves as the regional television centre for [BBC South West](/BBC_South_West) <sup>[181]</sup>. A team of dedicated journalists are headquartered in Plymouth for the [ITV West Country](/ITV_West_Country) regional station, following a rather predictable merger with [ITV West](/ITV_West) which forced [ITV Westcountry](/ITV_Westcountry) to cease operations on 16 February 2009 <sup>[182]</sup>. The main local newspapers serving Plymouth are *[The Herald](/The_Herald_(Plymouth))*, *[Western Morning News](/Western_Morning_News)*, and the *Plymouth Chronicle*. For radio listeners, [Greatest Hits Radio Plymouth](/Radio_Plymouth), [BBC Radio Devon](/BBC_Radio_Devon), and [Heart West](/Heart_West) are the local stations with the largest audiences <sup>[183]</sup>. A rather comprehensive media landscape.

## Sport

*   Main article: [Sport in Plymouth](/Sport_in_Plymouth)

[[File:Home Park (Plymouth Argyle FC) - panoramio.jpg|thumb|[Home Park](/Home_Park)]]
[[File:Plymouth Pavilions, home of the Plymouth Raiders.jpg|thumb|Plymouth Pavilions, home to the [Plymouth City Patriots](/Plymouth_City_Patriots).]]

Plymouth is home to [Plymouth Argyle F.C.](/Plymouth_Argyle_F.C.), who, as of the 2025-26 season, find themselves competing in the third tier of English football, Sky Bet League One. The team's home ground, rather conveniently located next to [Central Park](/Central_Park,_Plymouth), is aptly named [Home Park](/Home_Park) <sup>[184]</sup>. The club rather proudly links itself with the group of English non-conformists who, in 1620, famously departed Plymouth for the [New World](/New_World); hence, their enduring nickname, "The Pilgrims" <sup>[185]</sup>. The city also hosts three [Non-League football](/Non-League_football) clubs: [Plymouth Parkway](/Plymouth_Parkway_F.C.), who play at Bolitho Park; [Elburton Villa](/Elburton_Villa_F.C.), who call Haye Road home; and Plymstock United, who compete at Dean Cross. Plymouth Parkway earned promotion to the [Western League](/Western_Football_League) from the [South West Peninsula League](/South_West_Peninsula_League) in 2018, and after two rather inconveniently Covid-19 interrupted years, ascended to the [Southern Football League](/Southern_Football_League) in 2021. Meanwhile, Elburton Villa and Plymstock United continue their spirited competition in the South West Peninsula League <sup>[citation needed]</sup>.

Other sports clubs that rather bravely compete in national competitions include [Plymouth Albion](/Plymouth_Albion_R.F.C.), [Plymouth City Patriots](/Plymouth_City_Patriots), [Plymouth Raiders](/Plymouth_Raiders), and [Plymouth Gladiators](/Plymouth_Gladiators).

[Plymouth Albion Rugby Football Club](/Plymouth_Albion_Rugby_Football_Club) is a [rugby union](/Rugby_union) club that traces its origins back to 1875. They are currently competing in the third tier of Professional English Rugby, the [National League 1](/National_League_1), playing their home matches at [the Brickfields](/The_Brickfields) <sup>[186]</sup>.

In the realm of [basketball](/Basketball), the city is represented by two teams: [Plymouth City Patriots](/Plymouth_City_Patriots), who compete in the top-tier [British Basketball League](/British_Basketball_League), and [Plymouth Raiders](/Plymouth_Raiders), who play in the [National Basketball League](/National_Basketball_League_(England)).

[Plymouth Gladiators](/Plymouth_Gladiators) are a [speedway](/Motorcycle_speedway) team, currently competing in the British [National League](/National_League_(speedway)), with their home meetings taking place at the [Plymouth Coliseum](/St_Boniface_Arena). [Plymouth cricket club](/Plymouth_cricket_club), established in 1843, sees its current 1st XI playing in the Devon Premier League. Plymouth is also home to Plymouth Marjons Hockey Club, whose 1st XI competed in the National League last season. The Plymouth Mariners [Baseball](/Baseball) club plays in the South West Baseball League, holding their home games at Wilson Field in Central Park. Plymouth was also, for a time, home to an [American football](/American_football) club, the [Plymouth Admirals](/Plymouth_Admirals), until 2010 <sup>[citation needed]</sup>.

Plymouth, with its undeniable maritime heritage, serves as an important centre for watersports, particularly [scuba diving](/Scuba_diving) and [sailing](/Sailing). The Port of Plymouth Regatta holds the distinction of being one of the oldest regattas in the world, having been held with remarkable regularity since 1823. In September 2011, Plymouth had the honour of hosting the [America's Cup World Series](/America%27s_Cup_World_Series) for a period of nine days <sup>[187]</sup>. A brief moment in the international sporting spotlight.

## Public services

[[File:Devonport Leat on Dartmoor looking up stream - geograph.org.uk - 1656209.jpg|thumb|The [Devonport Leat](/Devonport_Leat) on [Dartmoor](/Dartmoor) looking up stream]]

Since 1973, Plymouth has been rather reliably supplied with water by [South West Water](/South_West_Water). Prior to this takeover, in 1973, the supply was managed by the Plymouth County Borough Corporation <sup>[188]</sup>. Before the 19th century, two [leats](/Leat) were ingeniously constructed to channel drinking water to the town, carrying it all the way from [Dartmoor](/Dartmoor) to Plymouth. One such watercourse, known as Plymouth or [Drake's Leat](/Drake%27s_Leat), was inaugurated on 24 April 1591, designed to tap the waters of the [River Meavy](/River_Meavy) <sup>[189]</sup>. The [Devonport Leat](/Devonport_Leat) was subsequently constructed to convey fresh drinking water to the rapidly expanding town of [Devonport](/Devonport,_Devon) and its ever-growing dockyard. It drew its supply from three Dartmoor rivers: The [West Dart](/West_Dart_River), Cowsic, and Blackabrook. It appears to have been operational since 1797, though its official completion date is recorded as 1801. Originally intended to supply water directly to Devonport town, it has since been shortened and now, rather pragmatically, carries water to [Burrator Reservoir](/Burrator_Reservoir), which, in turn, supplies the majority of Plymouth's water needs <sup>[190]</sup>. Burrator Reservoir itself is located approximately 5 miles (8 km) north of the city and was initially constructed in 1898, undergoing expansion in 1928 <sup>[191]</sup>.

[[File:Plymouth Combined Crown and County Court Centre - geograph.org.uk - 1656133.jpg|thumb|The [Plymouth Combined Crown and County Court Centre](/Plymouth_Law_Courts)]]

[Plymouth City Council](/Plymouth_City_Council) holds the rather unenviable responsibility for waste management across the city, while [South West Water](/South_West_Water) is, rather aptly, responsible for sewerage <sup>[192]</sup><sup>[193]</sup>. Plymouth's electricity supply is drawn from the [National Grid](/National_Grid_(UK)) and distributed throughout the city via [Western Power Distribution](/Western_Power_Distribution) <sup>[194]</sup>. On the outskirts of [Plympton](/Plympton), a [combined cycle](/Combined_cycle) gas-powered station, the [Langage Power Station](/Langage_Power_Station), began generating electricity for Plymouth at the close of 2009 <sup>[195]</sup>.

[Her Majesty's Courts and Tribunals Service](/Her_Majesty%27s_Courts_and_Tribunals_Service) maintains a [magistrates' court](/Magistrates%27_court_(England_and_Wales)) and a [Combined Crown and County Court Centre](/Plymouth_Law_Courts) within the city <sup>[196]</sup><sup>[197]</sup>. The Plymouth Borough Police, initially formed in 1836, eventually merged to become part of the larger [Devon and Cornwall Constabulary](/Devon_and_Cornwall_Constabulary) <sup>[198]</sup>. Police stations are located at Charles Cross and Crownhill (which serves as the Divisional HQ), with smaller stations in Plympton and Plymstock <sup>[199]</sup>. The city also hosts one of the Devon and Cornwall Area [Crown Prosecution Service](/Crown_Prosecution_Service) Divisional offices <sup>[200]</sup>. Plymouth is served by five fire stations, strategically located in Camel's Head, [Crownhill](/Crownhill), [Greenbank](/Greenbank,_Plymouth), [Plympton](/Plympton), and [Plymstock](/Plymstock), all operating under the umbrella of [Devon and Somerset Fire and Rescue Service](/Devon_and_Somerset_Fire_and_Rescue_Service) <sup>[201]</sup>. The [Royal National Lifeboat Institution](/Royal_National_Lifeboat_Institution) maintains an [Atlantic 85 class lifeboat](/Atlantic_85_class_lifeboat) and a [Severn class lifeboat](/Severn_class_lifeboat) stationed at [Millbay Docks](/Millbay_Docks) <sup>[202]</sup>.

Plymouth is medically served by Plymouth Hospitals [NHS Trust](/NHS_Trust), with the city's primary [NHS](/National_Health_Service_(England)) hospital being [Derriford Hospital](/Derriford_Hospital), located approximately 4 miles (6 km) north of the city centre. The Royal Eye Infirmary is also conveniently situated at Derriford Hospital <sup>[203]</sup>. The [South Western Ambulance Service](/South_Western_Ambulance_Service) NHS Foundation Trust operates within Plymouth and the wider south west region, with its headquarters located in [Exeter](/Exeter) <sup>[204]</sup>.

The mid-19th-century burial ground at [Ford Park Cemetery](/Ford_Park_Cemetery) was rather commendably reopened by a successful trust formed in 2000 <sup>[205]</sup>. The City council also manages two large early 20th-century cemeteries, at [Weston Mill](/Weston_Mill) and [Efford](/Efford), both of which are equipped with crematoria and chapels <sup>[206]</sup>. Additionally, there is a privately owned cemetery on the city's outskirts, Drake Memorial Park, which, in a rather unconventional approach, does not permit headstones to mark graves, opting instead for brass plaques set flush into the ground <sup>[207]</sup>. A rather understated approach to remembrance.

## Landmarks and tourist attractions

[[File:Foulston's Town Hall, Column and Library in Devonport.jpg|thumb|Grade I listed Town Hall, Column and Library in Devonport]]
[[File:Elliot Terrace, Plymouth Hoe - geograph.org.uk - 128453.jpg|thumb|Elliot Terrace, Plymouth Hoe]]

Following the conclusion of the rather unpleasant [English Civil War](/English_Civil_War), the imposing [Royal Citadel](/Royal_Citadel,_Plymouth) was erected in 1666 towards the eastern section of [Plymouth Hoe](/Plymouth_Hoe). Its purpose was twofold: to defend the port from potential naval attacks and, perhaps more pointedly, to suppress any lingering Plymothian Parliamentary leanings, while also serving as a training ground for the armed forces. Currently, for those with a penchant for historical fortifications, guided tours are available during the summer months <sup>[28]</sup>. Further to the west stands [Smeaton's Tower](/Smeaton%27s_Tower), a rather iconic lighthouse originally constructed in 1759, some 14 miles (23 km) offshore. This structure was, in a remarkable feat of engineering and preservation, dismantled in 1877, and its top two-thirds were meticulously reassembled on [Plymouth Hoe](/Plymouth_Hoe) <sup>[208]</sup>. It is now open to the public, offering panoramic views over the [Plymouth Sound](/Plymouth_Sound) and the city from its lantern room <sup>[209]</sup>. Plymouth is also home to 20 war memorials, nine of which are prominently displayed on [The Hoe](/Plymouth_Hoe). These include the [Plymouth Naval Memorial](/Plymouth_Naval_Memorial), a poignant tribute to those lost in World Wars I and II who have no known grave <sup>[210]</sup>, and the [Armada Memorial](/Armada_Memorial), commemorating the decisive defeat of the [Spanish Armada](/Spanish_Armada) <sup>[211]</sup>. A rather sombre collection of historical markers.

The early port settlement of Plymouth, originally known as "Sutton," roughly corresponds to the area now rather charmingly referred to as the [Barbican](/Barbican,_Plymouth). This historic quarter boasts an impressive 100 [listed buildings](/Listed_building) and the highest concentration of [cobbled](/Cobblestone) streets in Britain <sup>[212]</sup>. It was from near the commemorative [Mayflower Steps](/Mayflower_Steps) in Sutton Pool that the [Pilgrim Fathers](/Pilgrim_Fathers) embarked on their momentous journey to the [New World](/New_World) in 1620 <sup>[213]</sup>. Also situated on Sutton Pool is the [National Marine Aquarium](/National_Marine_Aquarium,_Plymouth), which proudly showcases 400 different marine species and features Britain's deepest aquarium tank <sup>[214]</sup>. A rather comprehensive collection of aquatic life.

A mile (two kilometres) upstream on the opposite side of the [River Plym](/River_Plym) lies the [Saltram estate](/Saltram_House), home to a magnificent [Jacobean](/Jacobean_architecture) and [Georgian](/Georgian_architecture) mansion <sup>[215]</sup>.

On the northern outskirts of the city, [Crownhill Fort](/Crownhill_Fort) stands as a remarkably well-restored example of a "[Palmerston's Folly](/Palmerston_forts)." It is owned by the [Landmark Trust](/Landmark_Trust) and is, rather conveniently, open to the public <sup>[216]</sup>.

To the west of the city lies [Devonport](/Devonport,_Devon), one of Plymouth's historically rich quarters. As part of Devonport's millennium regeneration project, the Devonport Heritage Trail has been introduced, complete with over 70 waymarkers meticulously outlining the route <sup>[217]</sup>.

Plymouth, for those with a desire to explore beyond its immediate confines, is frequently utilized as a convenient base for visitors venturing into [Dartmoor](/Dartmoor), the [Tamar](/River_Tamar) Valley, and the picturesque beaches of south-east [Cornwall](/Cornwall) <sup>[218]</sup>. [Kingsand](/Kingsand), [Cawsand](/Cawsand), and [Whitsand Bay](/Whitsand_Bay) are particularly popular destinations <sup>[219]</sup>.

The [Roland Levinsky Building](/Roland_Levinsky_Building), an undeniable landmark within the [University of Plymouth](/University_of_Plymouth), is situated in the city's central quarter. Designed by the esteemed architect [Henning Larsen](/Henning_Larsen), the building was officially opened in 2008 and currently houses the University's Arts faculty <sup>[220]</sup>.

[Beckley Point](/Beckley_Point), soaring to a height of 78m (20 floors), holds the distinction of being Plymouth's tallest building <sup>[221]</sup><sup>[222]</sup>. It was completed on 8 February 2018, having been designed by Boyes Rees Architects and constructed by contractors [Kier](/Kier_Group).

