## Notable people

*   Main article: [List of people from Plymouth](/List_of_people_from_Plymouth)

[[File:Sir Francis Drake.jpg|thumb|Sir [Francis Drake](/Francis_Drake)]]

Individuals hailing from Plymouth are rather predictably known as Plymothians, or, in a more informal and colloquial manner, as [Janners](/Janner) <sup>[223]</sup>. The term "Janner" is described as referring to a person from [Devon](/Devon), deriving from "Cousin Jan" (the [Devon](/Devon) form of [John](/John_(first_name))), but more specifically, within [naval](/Royal_Navy) circles, it denotes anyone from the Plymouth area <sup>[224]</sup>.

The illustrious Elizabethan navigator, Sir [Francis Drake](/Francis_Drake), though born in the nearby town of [Tavistock](/Tavistock,_Devon), served as the mayor of Plymouth, a rather significant local role <sup>[225]</sup>. He holds the distinction of being the first [Englishman](/English_people) to circumnavigate the world, and was known to the Spanish, rather ominously, as *El Draco*, meaning "The Dragon," after his rather disruptive raids on many of their ships <sup>[226]</sup>. He met his end, rather unglamorously, from [dysentery](/Dysentery) in 1596 off the coast of [Portobelo](/Portobelo), Panama <sup>[227]</sup>. In 2002, a mission to recover his body and return it to Plymouth was, rather surprisingly, sanctioned by the [Ministry of Defence](/Ministry_of_Defence_(United_Kingdom)) <sup>[228]</sup>. His cousin and contemporary, [John Hawkins](/John_Hawkins_(naval_commander)), was also a Plymouth man.

The esteemed painter Sir [Joshua Reynolds](/Joshua_Reynolds), who went on to found and serve as the first president of the [Royal Academy](/Royal_Academy), was born and educated in nearby [Plympton](/Plympton), an area now incorporated into Plymouth. [William Cookworthy](/William_Cookworthy), born in [Kingsbridge](/Kingsbridge), established his successful [porcelain](/Porcelain) business in the city and maintained a close friendship with [John Smeaton](/John_Smeaton), the innovative designer of the [Eddystone Lighthouse](/Eddystone_Lighthouse). [Benjamin Robert Haydon](/Benjamin_Robert_Haydon), an English painter renowned for his grand historical pictures, was born here in 1786 <sup>[229]</sup>. The naturalist [William Elford Leach](/William_Elford_Leach), who significantly contributed to paving the way in Britain for [Charles Darwin](/Charles_Darwin)'s revolutionary ideas, was born at Hoe Gate in 1791 <sup>[230]</sup>.

[Antarctic](/Antarctic) explorers [Robert Falcon Scott](/Robert_Falcon_Scott), who was actually born in Plymouth, and [Frank Bickerton](/Frank_Bickerton) both, at different times, resided in the city <sup>[231]</sup><sup>[232]</sup>. The artistic community includes [Beryl Cook](/Beryl_Cook), whose distinctive paintings often depicted the vibrant culture of Plymouth <sup>[233]</sup>, and [Robert Lenkiewicz](/Robert_Lenkiewicz), an artist whose provocative works explored themes of [vagrancy](/Vagrancy_(people)), sexual behaviour, and suicide, and who lived in the city from the 1960s until his death in 2002 <sup>[234]</sup>. Illustrator and creator of the beloved children's series *[Mr Benn](/Mr_Benn)* and *[King Rollo](/King_Rollo)*, [David McKee](/David_McKee), was born and raised in South Devon and received his artistic training at [Plymouth College of Art](/Plymouth_College_of_Art) <sup>[235]</sup>. Jazz musician [John Surman](/John_Surman), though born in nearby [Tavistock](/Tavistock,_Devon), maintains strong connections to the area, a fact evidenced by his 2012 album *[Saltash Bells](/Saltash_Bells)*. The [avant-garde](/Avant-garde) [prepared guitarist](/Prepared_guitar) [Keith Rowe](/Keith_Rowe) was born in the city <sup>[citation needed]</sup> before going on to establish the jazz [free improvisation](/Free_improvisation) band [AMM](/AMM_(group)) in London in 1965 and [MIMEO](/M.I.M.E.O.) in 1997. The musician and film director [Cosmo Jarvis](/Cosmo_Jarvis) has lived in several towns across South Devon and has utilized locations in and around Plymouth for filming his videos <sup>[236]</sup>. In the acting world, Sir [Donald Sinden](/Donald_Sinden) and [Judi Trott](/Judi_Trott) both claim Plymouth as their birthplace. George Passmore, one half of the [Turner Prize](/Turner_Prize)-winning duo [Gilbert and George](/Gilbert_and_George), was also born in the city, as was the Labour politician [Michael Foot](/Michael_Foot), whose family resides at the nearby [Trematon Castle](/Trematon_Castle) <sup>[237]</sup>.

Notable athletes from Plymouth include the swimmer [Sharron Davies](/Sharron_Davies) <sup>[238]</sup>, the diver [Tom Daley](/Tom_Daley_(diver)) <sup>[239]</sup>, the dancer [Wayne Sleep](/Wayne_Sleep) <sup>[240]</sup>, and the footballer [Trevor Francis](/Trevor_Francis) <sup>[241]</sup>. Other past residents of interest include the composer, journalist, and newspaper editor [William Henry Wills](/William_Henry_Wills_(journalist)), film music composer [Ron Goodwin](/Ron_Goodwin) <sup>[242]</sup>, and journalist [Angela Rippon](/Angela_Rippon) <sup>[243]</sup>, along with comedian [Dawn French](/Dawn_French). Canadian politician and legal scholar [Chris Axworthy](/Chris_Axworthy) also hailed from Plymouth <sup>[244]</sup>. The America-based actor [Donald Moffat](/Donald_Moffat), known for his roles as American Vice President [Lyndon B. Johnson](/Lyndon_B._Johnson) in the film *[The Right Stuff](/The_Right_Stuff_(film))*, and the fictional President Bennett in *[Clear and Present Danger](/Clear_and_Present_Danger_(film))*, was born in Plymouth <sup>[245]</sup>. Canadian actor [Mark Holden](/Mark_Holden_(actor)) also shares Plymouth as his birthplace. [Kevin Owen](/Kevin_Owen) is an international TV news anchor who was born in Freedom Fields Hospital, a detail perhaps only interesting to him, while his father served as a Royal Navy officer <sup>[citation needed]</sup>. The infamous Cambridge spy [Guy Burgess](/Guy_Burgess) was born at 2 Albemarle Villas, Stoke, during his father's service as a Royal Navy officer <sup>[246]</sup>. A rather eclectic mix of individuals, proving that Plymouth, like any city, is a crucible for all sorts of human endeavour.

